### FIFTH KHA*ND*A.

1\. 'The altar is Par*g*anya (the god of rain), O Gautama; its fuel is
the air itself, the smoke the cloud, the light the lightning, the coals.
the thunderbolt, the sparks the thunderings <span
id="fr_248"></span>[3](#fn_247.md).

<span id="page_79">p. 79</span>

2\. 'On that altar the Devas offer Soma, the king (the moon). From that
oblation rises rain <span id="fr_249"></span>[1](#fn_248.md).

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Footnotes

<span id="fn_247"></span>[78:3](sbe01099.htm#fr_248.md) Hrâduni, generally
explained by hail, but here by stanayitnu*s*abdâ*h*, rumblings.

<span id="fn_248"></span>[79:1](sbe01099.htm#fr_249.md) The water, which
had assumed the nature of Soma, now becomes rain.

